<TD width=441 valign=top bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TABLE width=441 valign=top cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10 border=0><TR><TD><FONT FACE="arial,helvetica,sans-serif" color="#000000">

<h2><font face="arial,helvetica">Little thoughts over a Big Mac</font></h2>

<h3><font face="arial,helvetica">A contemplation of the so-called Americanization of China</font></h3>


<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="5">
	<tr valign="top">
		<td><a href="/SPECIALS/1999/china.50/dispatches/images/link.bruce.kennedy.jpg"><img src="/SPECIALS/1999/china.50/dispatches/images/bruce.kennedy.jpg" alt="Kennedy" width="87" height="87" border="0"></a></td>
		<td><font face="arial,helvetica" size="2" color="#000000"><b>
By <a href="#bio"><font color="#0033CC">Bruce Kennedy</font></a><br>
CNN Interactive
		</b></font></td>
	</tr>
</table>



<!-- photo -->
<table align="right" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="5" width="214">
	<tr><td><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="top.lantern.jpg" alt="red lantern" width="214" height="164" border="0"></td></tr>
		<tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#000000"><b>
Red lantern, golden arches: Outside the McDonald's on Wangfujing Street
		</b></font></td><td width="12">&nbsp;</td></tr>
	</table></td></tr>
</table>
<!-- /photo -->


<p>
BEIJING (CNN) -- I went to a <a href="javascript:openWindow('link.pla.and.mcdonalds.html','windowname','toolbar=no,location=no,directories=no,status=no,menubar=no,scrollbars=yes,resizable=no,width=510,height=400')"><font color="#0033CC">McDonald's today</font></a> -- for purely journalistic reasons, mind you. It was a little past noon, and the place was just like any other McDonald's around the world -- <a href="javascript:openWindow('link.mcdonalds.interior.html','windowname','toolbar=no,location=no,directories=no,status=no,menubar=no,scrollbars=yes,resizable=no,width=510,height=400')"><font color="#0033CC">swamped at lunch</font></a>. 
</p>

<p>
There were some Chinese touches, of course. Ronald McDonald spoke in weepingly beautiful Mandarin from a videotape playing on a corner monitor. There was a laissez faire attitude at the counter -- no lines, just push your way through and establish eye contact.
</p>


<!-- notebook -->
